<section class="section section--alt" id="qbo-feat-sales-tax-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Automated Sales Tax, plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qbo-feat-sales-tax-in-brief-text">QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s Automated Sales Tax is the feature that figures out how much sales tax to charge on a sale &mdash; so you don&rsquo;t have to keep a spreadsheet of rates by city and county. When you create an invoice or sales receipt, QBO reads the customer&rsquo;s shipping or billing address, looks at the tax category you&rsquo;ve assigned to each product or service, checks the agencies where you&rsquo;ve set up nexus, and applies the correct combined state and local rate to the taxable lines. It then records the tax to a liability account and rolls it into a sales-tax liability report.</p>
      <p>The point worth understanding is that the calculation is only as good as the setup behind it. QBO automates the math; it doesn&rsquo;t know things you haven&rsquo;t told it. If a product is flagged taxable when it&rsquo;s exempt, if a customer&rsquo;s address is wrong, or if you have nexus in a state you never set up, the number on the invoice will be confidently wrong. And QBO never decides <em>where</em> you owe tax or <em>files</em> the return &mdash; nexus is a determination for you and your CPA, the rates and rules are the states&rsquo;, and filing happens on each agency&rsquo;s own schedule, in the agency&rsquo;s own portal.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

